- Maintaining monetary stability within the framework of the linked exchange rate system;  
- Promoting the stability and soundness of the financial system (including the banking system);  
- Assisting in consolidating Hong Kong's status as an international financial center, including maintaining and developing Hong Kong's financial infrastructure; and  
- Managing the foreign exchange fund.

- Established a clear institutional governance framework;
- Maintained high accountability and transparency, and maintained close contact with all stakeholders; and
- Implemented sound and robust monitoring measures to manage risks and ensure that the conduct and daily operations of all levels of staff comply with specified standards.

- Promote the overall stability and effective operation of the banking system;  
- Cooperate with other relevant institutions and organizations to develop the debt market;  
- Handle matters relating to the issuance and circulation of legal tender banknotes and coins;  
- Promote the safety and efficiency of financial infrastructure through the development of payment, clearing and settlement systems, and, where appropriate, be responsible for operating such systems; and  
- Cooperate with other relevant institutions and organizations to enhance confidence in Hong Kong’s monetary and financial systems, and implement appropriate market development measures to assist in strengthening Hong Kong’s international competitiveness in financial services.

- Certificates of Indebtedness (providing full backing for bank notes issued by the three note-issuing banks);
- Government-issued currency notes and coins;
- the aggregate balances of settlement accounts maintained with the HKMA (i.e. the total balance); and
- Exchange Fund Bills and Bonds issued by the HKMA on behalf of the Government.

- Co-hosted a joint climate finance conference with the Dubai Financial Services Authority in September;
- Co-hosted the 15th Global Risk Forum with the Global Association of Risk Professionals in October;
- Also co-hosted an international financial seminar with the Bank for International Settlements in October; and
- Held the Financial Stability Board plenary meeting in December, which was the first meeting of its kind in Asia since 2016, bringing together leaders and senior officials from over 50 national financial authorities and 12 international standard-setting bodies.

(i) Safeguarding capital;  
(ii) Ensuring that the overall monetary base is always fully supported by highly liquid U.S. dollar assets;  
(iii) Ensuring sufficient liquidity to maintain monetary and financial stability; and  
(iv) Striving to maximize investment returns, subject to the above (i) to (iii), in order to safeguard the long-term purchasing power of the foreign exchange fund.

- Bond investment gains of 13.59 billion Hong Kong dollars;  
- Stock investment gains of 9.09 billion Hong Kong dollars (of which 2.18 billion Hong Kong dollars from Hong Kong stock investments and 6.91 billion Hong Kong dollars from investments in other stocks);  
- A downward adjustment of 3.56 billion Hong Kong dollars in the foreign exchange valuation of non-Hong Kong dollar assets; and  
- Other investment gains of 2.76 billion Hong Kong dollars held by subsidiaries of the Exchange Fund Investment Holdings.
